Module 4 Lab: Human Activity Recognition w/ KNN & Cross-Validation

Author

Ben Falandays

Learning Objectives

Our learning objectives for this module are:

  • Understand the bias-variance tradeoff (accuracy vs overfitting)
  • Understand the k-nearest neighbors algorithm for classification and implement it with tidymodels
  • Use cross-validation to tune the value of k

Our cellphones and smartwatches record a lot of different kinds of data. Thereâs our search history and web traffic, of course, but also GPS, audio data, and a variety of sensors, including a gyroscope, accelerometer, and gravity sensor. In this module, weâll see how that sensor data can be used to predict what a user is doing during some interval of timeâwhether theyâre sitting down, riding a bike, driving a car, etc. This type of analysis could be useful for a tech company to figure out your interests and serve up targeted ads, or to deliver content/functionality at just the right moment (e.g.Â maybe you want your maps interface to change automatically depending upon whether you are biking, driving, or walking).

The dataset for this module contains summarized data (i.e.Â means, maxs, mins, etc) from the accelerometer, gyroscope, and gravity sensor of a smartwatch while participants performed various actions. We will use the k-nearest neighbors (knn) algorithm to classify the activity being performed. Then, we will use k-fold cross-validation to tune the parameters of our knn model in order to get the highest classification accuracy, while avoiding overfitting.

Here is where we might bore students with some minutia or a formula like \(\hat{y} = \alpha + \beta x\).

Data visualization and exploration

Exercise 1

First, make a bar plot showing the number of observations of each type of Activity.

ggplot(df, aes(x = Activity, fill = Activity))+geom_bar()

One thing to notice is that we have substantial âclass imbalance,â meaning there are many observations of some activitiesâsuch as cycling and footballâand far fewer observations of other activities, such as jogging and pushups. Class imbalance can cause problems for our model, because the training data is driven much more strongly by only a subset of activities.

To deal with this problem, we can use resampling techniques. We can either âupsample,â resample rows from classes with fewer observations, or âdownsample,â excluding rows from classes with more observations.

In this case, we will try upsampling using the step_upsample() function. We set over_ratio to .5, meaning we will oversample the classes with fewer observations until they have 50% as many observations as the class with the most observations. The plot below shows what the distribution of activities will look like after this resampling step.

recipe(Activity ~ ., df) %>% 
  step_upsample(Activity, over_ratio = .5) %>% 
  prep() %>%
  bake(new_data = NULL) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Activity, fill = Activity))+geom_bar() +
  geom_bar()

Next, weâll explore the data a bit to see what it looks like while doing different activities. Notice that there are a LOT of variables in the dataset. First, weâll just grab any two variables and make a scatterplot, with points colored by Activity. I chose the mean of the accelerometer data in the X- and Y-axes, called ACCELEROMETER_X_mean and ACCELEROMETER_Y_mean

ggplot(df, aes(x = ACCELEROMETER_X_mean, y = ACCELEROMETER_Y_mean, color = as.factor(Activity))) + geom_point()

We can see that the data is somewhat clustered. For example, there is a cloud of points associated with swimming, another for cycling and for football. But overall, itâs pretty messy, and it would probably be hard to accurately predict the activity from this data.

Exercise 2

Next, make the same plot as above using the X- and Y-axis means of the gravity sensor, and another for the gyroscope data. Do you notice any differences? Which pair of variables do you think would be best for predicting Activity?

ggplot(df, aes(x = GRAVITY_X_mean, y = GRAVITY_Y_mean, color = as.factor(Activity))) + geom_point()

Our dataset has a lot of different (potential) predictor variablesâ112, to be precise. As such, we can think of each row as a point in a 112-dimensional space. Above, we plotted the data in 3 different, 2-dimensional slices of that 112-D space. We can see that the datapoints appear more discriminable when we look at some dimensions rather than others. But how well could we tell the groups apart if we could see in all 112 dimensions at once?

The model weâll use today, the k-nearest neighbors (KNN) algorithm, is based on the distance between points. For any two points, we can measure their distance from each other in each of the 112 dimensions. KNN assumes that âbirds of a feather flock togetherââmeaning that observations from different Activity categories will cluster in distinct regions of this 112-dimensional space. When we encounter a new, unlabeled point and want to predict itâs class, KNN simply checks the class labels for the k nearest other points (in the training set) and takes their labels as âvotesâ to determine the label of the new point.

Tip

k (called neighbors in our model spec) should always be an odd number, to avoid ties in voting.

Data splitting

Using tidymodels, split the data into testing and training splits called df_test and df_train, respectively.

df_split = initial_split(df)
df_train <- training(df_split)
df_test <- testing(df_split)

Building a KNN model

Exercise 4

Next, make a model specification using tidymodels, for a k-nearest neighbors model. The function is called nearest_neighbor(). The mode should be set to âclassificationâ, the engine to âkknnâ, and letâs set neighbors to 5, to start.

knn_spec <- nearest_neighbor(
  mode = "classification",
  engine = "kknn",
  neighbors = 5
)
Exercise 5

Below, I supply you with a recipe, rec, that deals with upsampling. Finish building a workflow called knn_wf, by adding your model specification, as well as the upsampling recipe.

rec <- recipe(Activity ~ ., df) %>% 
  step_upsample(Activity, over_ratio = .5) 

knn_wf <- workflow() %>% 
  add_model(knn_spec) %>% 
  add_recipe(rec)

Fitting the model

Exercise 6

Next, fit the model to the training data.

knn_fit <-
  knn_wf %>% 
  fit(data = df_train)

knn_fit %>% 
  augment(df_train) %>% 
  metrics(Activity, .pred_class)

2 kap      multiclass     0.953

Keep in mind that the model we have built so far is just a starting pointâwe will need to tune the model in order to find the best parameter(s). For the k-nearest neighbors algorithm, there is just one model parameter: the value k (the number of neighbors considered). To find the best value for k, we will need to run the model with different values of k, and collect some metric of performance. But importantly, we donât want to use our testing data just yet to evaluate our modelsâthe test set must be saved for the final model.

Exercise 7

Explain WHY we donât want to evaluate model performance on the test set while we are tuning our model.

So how are we supposed to evaluate model performance for the purpose of parameter tuning, without using the test set? Thatâs where cross-validation comes in. We divide the data into n subsets, set aside one subset as the validation data, and train on the remaining subsets. We then repeat that procedure n times, each time leaving out a different subset of the data. This amounts to resampling the training set to use it as a preliminary test set. With this approach, we can test out different values of k (neighbors in the KNN) and estimate how each will perform, before tapping into our precious test set.

Model evaluation with cross-validation

Exercise 8

Use the vfold_cv() function from tidymodels to divide df_train into 5 folds. Then, use the fit_resamples() function to estimate the performance of our initial KNN model.

folds <- vfold_cv(df_train, v = 5)

knn_rs <- fit_resamples(
  knn_wf,
  folds,
  control = control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE)
)

collect_metrics(knn_rs)
# A tibble: 2 Ã 6
  .metric  .estimator  mean     n std_err .config             
  <chr>    <chr>      <dbl> <int>   <dbl> <chr>               
1 accuracy multiclass 0.830     5 0.00800 Preprocessor1_Model1
2 roc_auc  hand_till  0.914     5 0.00325 Preprocessor1_Model1

Model tuning

Next, we will tune the model to find the best value of k (neighbors). We essentially just repeat the process above for different values of k, but weâll do it in a nice tidymodels way.

tune_spec <- nearest_neighbor(
  mode = "classification",
  engine = "kknn",
  neighbors = tune()
)

# Make a grid of values of _k_ (`neighbors`) to try -- I use odd numbers (to avoid voting ties) from 1-19
neighbor_grid <- tibble(neighbors = seq(1,19,by=2)) 

tune_wf <- workflow() %>%
  add_formula(Activity ~ .) %>%
  step_upsample(Activity, over_ratio = .5) %>%
  add_model(tune_spec)

tune_rs <- tune_grid(
  tune_wf,
  folds,
  grid = neighbor_grid,
  control = control_resamples(save_pred = TRUE)
)

#collect_metrics(tune_rs)
autoplot(tune_rs)

chosen_n <- tune_rs %>% select_by_one_std_err(metric = "roc_auc", neighbors)

final_knn <- finalize_workflow(tune_wf, chosen_n)

knn_fit <- fit(final_knn, df_train)

knn_fit %>% 
  extract_fit_parsnip()
